## The Half of Security That Does Not Run on Servers

Day 50 documented the technical controls — encryption, authentication, audit logging, boundary protection. Today covers the controls that live in people, processes, and policies rather than in configuration files and code.

This half of the security program is harder to document well than the technical half, for a specific reason: technical controls either work or they do not. You can screenshot an RDS instance showing encryption enabled. You cannot screenshot a culture of security awareness, a consistently followed incident response process, or a genuinely functional change management review. Administrative controls require documentation that describes what should happen, evidence that it does happen, and records that demonstrate the frequency and quality of execution.

The SSP documentation challenge for administrative controls is therefore different from technical controls. For technical controls, the challenge is precision — documenting the exact configuration so an assessor knows what to verify. For administrative controls, the challenge is demonstrating operational reality — documenting not just what the procedure says but how the organization knows it is being followed.

