## What Actually Clicked for Me

The framing that clarified administrative control documentation today is the difference between a *policy reference* and an *implementation description*.

A policy reference says: "Security awareness training is required per MyClinic Policy SEC-AT-001." That tells an assessor that a policy exists. It does not tell them who delivers the training, how completion is tracked, what happens when someone does not complete it on time, or whether the training content actually covers the threats relevant to OpenMRS.

An implementation description says: who does what, when, how frequently, how compliance is verified, what happens when compliance fails, and where the evidence lives. The implementation description makes the assessor's job possible — they can request the specific evidence and verify that the control is operating as described.

When I write administrative control implementation descriptions with this standard in mind, two things happen. First, the descriptions become useful operational documents — the ISSO or any responsible party can read them and know exactly what they are supposed to do. Second, gaps become visible — if I cannot write "compliance is verified by [specific mechanism]" because there is no verification mechanism, that is a gap that belongs in the POA&M.

