## Documenting Gaps Honestly

Three administrative control gaps surfaced during today's documentation that belong in the POA&M:

**Gap 1 — Clinical downtime procedures (CP-2, CP-3):** Not complete. Draft exists. Target completion and test before authorization. Owner: Health IT Manager and ISSO jointly.

**Gap 2 — IR-3 technical response simulation:** Annual tabletop implemented. Full technical simulation not yet conducted. Target: complete before authorization package finalized. Owner: ISSO.

**Gap 3 — AT-3 role-based training — clinical downtime component:** Cannot be fully delivered until CP-2 clinical downtime procedures are complete. Dependent on Gap 1 resolution.

These gaps do not prevent the authorization process from moving forward — they become POA&M items with documented remediation plans that the AO reviews as part of the authorization decision. An AO reviewing an honest SSP that documents gaps with remediation plans is in a better position than one reviewing an SSP that describes those controls as fully implemented when they are not.

Honest SSP documentation with identified gaps and a credible remediation plan is a stronger authorization package than a document that claims full implementation of controls that do not actually exist.

