## What I Am Still Thinking About

One challenge in administrative control documentation that I want to think through carefully: how should the SSP document controls that depend on individual judgment rather than defined procedures?

The security impact analysis (CM-4) is an example. The process I documented requires the ISSO to evaluate whether a change affects any security control implementation. But "evaluate" is a judgment call — the quality of the assessment depends on the ISSO's knowledge and attention, not on a checklist.

Some organizations address this by creating structured security impact analysis templates — a checklist of questions the reviewer must answer for each change. That converts the judgment call into a documented evaluation with an audit trail. The assessor can then review completed templates and evaluate whether the questions are the right questions, and whether the answers are plausible.

I want to add a security impact analysis template to the CM documentation — not because the ISSO cannot make good judgment calls without one, but because the template creates consistent, reviewable evidence that the analysis happened and covered the right considerations. That is useful both for assessment and for continuity when the ISSO role changes.

